  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "However, these techniques are not well suited to find the global optimal conditions and scale exponentially with the number of variables.Computational approaches that rely on optimization algorithms offer more efficient ways to obtain the optimal conditions, without requiring an exponential number of experiments per variable to be optimized.",
    "Early examples of chemical reaction conditions optimization through computational approaches focused on the application of black-box optimization algorithms, such as steepest descent, SNOBFIT, and Nelder-Mead simplex, which demonstrated positive results and the ability to perform self-optimizing automated workflows with little human intervention [57,58,60,62,[73][74][75].",
    "In recent years, ML optimization methods have demonstrated the ability to obtain optimal reaction conditions within a reduced number of experiments in comparison to human intuition, traditional DOE, and other black-box optimization algorithms [2,76,77].",
    "Unlike traditional optimization algorithms, the ML approach focuses on building predictive surrogate models for objective functions.",
    "These models learned the relationships between the reaction conditions and the target optimization objectives based on experimental data."
  ],
